Photo by @amivitale. Rahima Begum holds her one day old baby inside a slum in Dhaka, Bangladesh. She had been displaced because of rising waters and a changing climate and forced to migrate to the slums of Dhaka. Bangladesh is among the most densely populated countries in the world, where 28,000 people live per square kilometer in its capital city of Dhaka. The slum has no permanent sanitation and sewage facilities. As the sea level, and the temperature rise, bringing greater and more destructive storms and droughts, there is increasing awareness about climate refugees, whose numbers could far surpass refugees driven by conflict. Currently, however, there are no legal protections for those displaced by climate, and the penalty for inaction on climate change grows only more severe by the year. It will be felt most severely by those who least contribute to global warming.

I recently took over the @everydayrefugees @Instagram account to help people better understand the challenges millions of displaced persons around the world face and the ways in which you can get involved. To learn more, including how to help, follow @friendshipngo @unfccc @unicef @theirc @doctorswithoutborders and others working on the front lines.

